var definitions = ['<h2>Dieser Wagen kann sehr schnell fahren.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative adjective in German, meaning "this" in English. It specifies a particular thing close to the speaker and agrees with the masculine noun "Wagen" in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>Wagen</strong> This is a masculine noun in German, which means "car" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>kann</strong> This is a modal verb in German, which corresponds to "can" in English, indicating ability or possibility. It is conjugated in the third-person singular present tense to match the subject "Wagen".</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "very". It is used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>schnell</strong> This is an adjective in German, meaning "fast" in English. When used with the verb "fahren", it describes the manner in which the car can move.</div><div><strong>fahren</strong> This is the infinitive form of a German verb meaning "to drive" or "to travel by vehicle" in English. The infinitive form is used here because modal verbs like "kann" are usually followed by an infinitive verb.</div>','<h2>Dieser Stuhl scheint fragil.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this" in English. It is used here to point out a specific chair and it is in the nominative masculine singular form to agree with the noun it describes.</div><div><strong>Stuhl</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in German, which means "chair" in English. It is the subject of the sentence. In the nominative case, it matches the demonstrative pronoun "dieser".</div><div><strong>scheint</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "scheinen", which means "to seem" or "to appear" in English. It is used to express an impression or appearance of the subject.</div><div><strong>fragil</strong> This is an adjective borrowed from Latin, meaning "fragile" in English. It describes the condition or state of the chair, implying that the chair looks like it may easily break.</div>','<h2>Dieser Affe spielt mit dem Seil.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun for "this" in the masculine nominative case, referring to a male noun that is close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Affe</strong> This is the German word for "monkey" or "ape". It’s a masculine noun and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>spielt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play".</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is the German preposition for "with", indicating the use of or interaction with an object.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is the German definite article for "the" in the masculine or neuter dative case, corresponding to the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>Seil</strong> This is the German word for "rope". It is a neuter noun in the dative case due to it being the object of the preposition "mit".</div>','<h2>Dieses Gebäude ist hoch.</h2><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, which means "this". It is used here in the neuter nominative case to refer to the building, which is neuter in German.</div><div><strong>Gebäude</strong> This is a neutral noun in German, which means "building". In this sentence, it is the subject and follows the demonstrative pronoun to form "this building".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject of the sentence to its descriptor.</div><div><strong>hoch</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "tall" or "high". It describes the property of the building being referred to in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Dieses Hemd ist weiß.</h2><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this". It is neuter to match the gender of the noun "Hemd".</div><div><strong>Hemd</strong> This is a neuter noun in German meaning "shirt". It’s the subject of the sentence here.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject with its description.</div><div><strong>weiß</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "white". It describes the color of the shirt, and it does not need to be declined here as it is in predicate position.</div>','<h2>Wir werden dieses Kanu nehmen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the German word for "we". It is a first-person plural pronoun and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is a German auxiliary verb used to form the future tense. In this sentence, it is helping to express a future action—a plan or intention.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this". It’s the neuter nominative singular form agreeing with the noun "Kanu".</div><div><strong>Kanu</strong> This is a German noun that means "canoe". It is the direct object of the sentence and is in the accusative case following the pronoun "dieses".</div><div><strong>nehmen</strong> This is the main verb in its infinitive form, meaning "to take". In this sentence, it indicates the action that the subject ("we") intends to perform in the future. It is used here with the auxiliary verb "werden" to indicate future tense.</div>','<h2>Ich liebe diese Gitarre.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the German pronoun for "I", representing the first-person singular subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>liebe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "lieben", which means "to love". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, which translates to "this" in English. It is used here to specify the noun that follows, and it must agree with the gender, number, and case of that noun.</div><div><strong>Gitarre</strong> This word is a feminine noun in German, meaning "guitar". It is the direct object of the verb "lieben", indicating the thing that is being loved.</div>','<h2>Diese Blume ist schön.</h2><div><strong>Diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "this" in English. It agrees in gender, case, and number with the noun it refers to, which is feminine singular here.</div><div><strong>Blume</strong> This is the German word for "flower". It is a feminine singular noun and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Blume" with the adjective "schön".</div><div><strong>schön</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "beautiful" or "nice". It modifies the noun "Blume" and, in the nominative case, agrees with the feminine singular subject.</div>','<h2>Ich habe diese Brieftasche gefunden.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it’s used to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "this" in English. It’s used here to specify the noun that follows, which is "Brieftasche" (wallet).</div><div><strong>Brieftasche</strong> This is a feminine noun in German, meaning "wallet". It’s the direct object of the sentence, indicating what the speaker has found.</div><div><strong>gefunden</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "finden", which means "to find". In combination with the auxiliary verb "habe", it forms the present perfect tense, which is used to describe past events that are connected to the present.</div>','<h2>Ich will diese Schuhe.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>will</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "wollen", which means "to want". It indicates the speaker’s desire or intention.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "these" in English. It is used here to specify which shoes the speaker is referring to, implying they are close by or have been previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>Schuhe</strong> This is the German word for "shoes". It is a plural noun, hence matching with the plural demonstrative pronoun "diese".</div>','<h2>Diese Beeren sind köstlich.</h2><div><strong>Diese</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun for "these", used to indicate specific objects close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Beeren</strong> This is the German noun for "berries". It is a plural form, referring to more than one berry.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Beeren" with the adjective "köstlich".</div><div><strong>köstlich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "delicious" or "tasty". It describes the quality of the berries and agrees in number and case with the noun "Beeren".</div>','<h2>Ich werde diese Filme ausleihen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which means "will" in English. It’s used here to form the future tense, indicating a future action.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "these" in English. It refers to specific items or concepts close to the speaker, in this case, "Filme" (movies).</div><div><strong>Filme</strong> This is the plural form of "Film", which means "movie" or "film" in English. Here, it’s the direct object of the sentence, representing the items being borrowed.</div><div><strong>ausleihen</strong> This is the verb meaning "to borrow" or "to rent" in German. It’s an infinitive placed at the end of the sentence, as is common in German sentence structure when an auxiliary verb is present.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Dieser Mantel gehört mir.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is the masculine singular form of the demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this". It refers to a nearby subject, in this case, the coat. The form agrees with the noun it describes, which is masculine in gender and singular in number.</div><div><strong>Mantel</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in German which means "coat". It is the subject of the sentence and what the sentence is about.</div><div><strong>gehört</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "gehören", which means "to belong to". It indicates possession or ownership in this context.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular dative pronoun in German, equivalent to "me" in English. It indicates to whom the coat belongs, which in this sentence is the speaker themselves.</div>','<h2>Dieser Karton ist deiner.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this" in English. It is used to specify a particular object that is close to the speaker, and it’s in the nominative masculine singular form to agree with the noun it modifies.</div><div><strong>Karton</strong> This is a masculine noun in German that translates to "carton" or "box" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject of the sentence to the predicate.</div><div><strong>deiner</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the nominative masculine singular form in German, equivalent to "yours" in English. It indicates ownership, relating the carton to the person spoken to.</div>','<h2>Dieser Hund ist sehr groß.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "this" in English. It’s used here in the masculine nominative case to point out or specify a particular male or neutral gender noun, in this case, "Hund" (dog).</div><div><strong>Hund</strong> This is a masculine noun in German and it means "dog". It’s in the nominative case because it’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject with an adjective to describe its state of being.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English. It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>groß</strong> This is an adjective that means "large" or "big" in English. In the sentence, it is used in the positive degree to describe the size of the dog.</div>','<h2>Dieser Kuchen ist für euch.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun for "this" in the masculine nominative singular form. It refers to a masculine or neutral noun that is close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Kuchen</strong> This is a German noun meaning "cake". It is masculine and here it’s in the nominative case as it is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject of the sentence to the predicate.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a German preposition that means "for". It indicates the beneficiary or recipient of an action.</div><div><strong>euch</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" (plural) in English. It serves as the indirect object of the sentence, indicating who the cake is intended for.</div>','<h2>Dieser Baum ist wirklich groß.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun for "this" in masculine nominative singular form. It points out a specific object that is close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Baum</strong> This is the German noun for "tree". It’s in the nominative case because it is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It’s used here to link the subject to its descriptor.</div><div><strong>wirklich</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "really" or "truly". It’s used here to emphasize the size of the tree.</div><div><strong>groß</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "big" or "tall". It describes the noun "Baum" and agrees with it in the masculine singular form.</div>','<h2>Dieser Staubsauger ist unserer.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German that translates to "this" in English. It’s placed before a masculine nominative singular noun and is used here to specify which vacuum cleaner is being talked about.</div><div><strong>Staubsauger</strong> This is a compound noun in German, "Staub" meaning "dust" and "sauger" from "saugen" meaning "to suck". Together they form "Staubsauger", which means "vacuum cleaner". It is the subject of the sentence and is in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It serves as a linking verb in this sentence, connecting the subject "Staubsauger" with the predicate "unserer".</div><div><strong>unserer</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the nominative masculine singular form and means "ours". It indicates that the vacuum cleaner belongs to the speaker and possibly others included with the speaker. The pronoun changes to agree with the gender, number, and case of the noun it is associated with.</div>','<h2>Dieser frische Zitronensaft ist sauer.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German which translates to "this" in English. It is used here in the masculine nominative singular form to point out or specify the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>frische</strong> This is the masculine nominative singular form of the adjective "frisch", which means "fresh" in English. It describes the quality of the noun it modifies.</div><div><strong>Zitronensaft</strong> This is a compound noun in German. "Zitrone" means "lemon", and "Saft" means "juice", so "Zitronensaft" translates to "lemon juice" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It functions as the main verb in the sentence, linking the subject to its complement.</div><div><strong>sauer</strong> This is an adjective meaning "sour" in English. It describes the taste of the lemon juice mentioned in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Es sind keine Männer in dieser Gruppe.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is a pronoun in German, often used as a placeholder subject, similar to the English word "it". In this sentence, it helps to form the existential construction ("there are").</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". In this context, it works together with "Es" to mean "there are".</div><div><strong>keine</strong> This is a negation phrase in German, composed of "kein" (a no/none/without article, used to negate nouns) and the plural ending "-e". It negates the existence of the noun that follows, indicating "no" or "not any".</div><div><strong>Männer</strong> This is the plural form of "Mann", which means "man". In plural, it refers to "men".</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German indicating location or position, in this sentence it introduces the place where the men are not.</div><div><strong>dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this". When used with a plural noun like "Gruppe", it becomes "dieser" to align with the feminine gender and dative case caused by the preposition "in".</div><div><strong>Gruppe</strong> This is a noun in German which means "group". It is feminine and receives the dative case after the preposition "in".</div>','<h2>Mensch! Dieser Typ liebt sich wirklich!</h2><div><strong>Mensch!</strong> This is an exclamation in German, similar to "Man!" or "Gee!" in English. It’s an informal expression often used to express surprise, irritation, or emphasis.</div><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this" in English. It is used to refer to a masculine noun, which in this case is "Typ".</div><div><strong>Typ</strong> This is a colloquial German word meaning "guy" or "dude" in English. It refers to a male person.</div><div><strong>liebt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "lieben", which means "to love" in English. It indicates that the action is being done by the "Typ" mentioned earlier.</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in German, equivalent to "himself" in English. It’s used here to indicate that the "Typ" is loving himself in a reflexive action.</div><div><strong>wirklich</strong> This is an adverb meaning "really" or "truly" in English. It’s used here to emphasize the extent to which the "Typ" is engaged in the action of loving himself.</div>','<h2>Ich glaube, dass dieser Stift seiner ist.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>glaube</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "glauben", which means "to believe". It indicates the action or opinion of the subject.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that introduces a subordinate clause. It translates to "that" in English and connects the main clause to the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the masculine nominative singular form, meaning "this" in English. It is used here to refer to "Stift" which is masculine in German.</div><div><strong>Stift</strong> This is a masculine noun in German, meaning "pen" in English. It is the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>seiner</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the masculine singular genitive case or masculine singular nominative case, meaning "his" in English. It indicates possession, that the pen belongs to "him", an unspecified male person.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It serves as the linking verb in the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Ich denke, dass dieser Film am lustigsten ist.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>denke</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "denken", which means "to think". Here it indicates the action or process of thinking.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that introduces a subordinate clause. It is equivalent to "that" in English.</div><div><strong>dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, in the nominative case, masculine singular. It means "this" and refers to "Film" which is masculine in German.</div><div><strong>Film</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "movie" or "film". It is the object of the demonstrative pronoun "dieser".</div><div><strong>am lustigsten</strong> This is a superlative form of the adjective "lustig", which means "funny" in English. "Am lustigsten" means "the funniest". In German, the construction "am + [superlative]" is used to express "the [superlative]".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject with the predicate adjective "am lustigsten".</div>','<h2>Ist dieses Haus ihres?</h2><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. In this sentence, it’s used to form a question.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the neuter singular accusative case in German, meaning "this". It refers to the noun "Haus" which is neuter in gender.</div><div><strong>Haus</strong> This is a neuter noun in the nominative singular case in German, meaning "house". In this sentence, it is the subject.</div><div><strong>ihres</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the genitive case, feminine or neuter singular, and is used to refer to something belonging to the third-person female or neuter singular ("her" or "its" in English). In this context, it implies the question "is this house hers?" or "is this house theirs?" referring to something owned by a person mentioned or known in the conversation.</div>','<h2>Okay. Ich nehme dieses Gericht.</h2><div><strong>Okay</strong> This word is a common interjection in many languages, including English and German. It indicates agreement or acknowledgment.</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nehme</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "nehmen", which means "to take" in English. It suggests the action of choosing or selecting something.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the nominative neutral singular form, meaning "this" in English. It’s used to specify a particular item that is close to the speaker, either physically or contextually.</div><div><strong>Gericht</strong> This is a German noun meaning "dish" or "course" in the context of food. The word also has other meanings, such as "court" in a legal context, but here it refers to a meal option.</div>','<h2>Dieses Haus hat kein Dach!</h2><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is a German demonstrative pronoun in the neuter nominative or accusative singular, equivalent to "this" in English. It refers to a nearby object, in this case, "Haus" (house).</div><div><strong>Haus</strong> This is a German neuter noun in the nominative singular, meaning "house". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the German verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or existence of something in this context.</div><div><strong>kein</strong> This is a negation article in German, equivalent to "no" in English. It negates the existence of something—in this case, "Dach" (roof).</div><div><strong>Dach</strong> This is a German neuter noun in the accusative singular, meaning "roof". It’s the direct object of the sentence, being what the house doesn’t have.</div>','<h2>Dieses Seil ist am längsten.</h2><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German and translates to "this" in English. It’s neuter nominative singular, agreeing with the noun "Seil" that follows, and is used to specify the particular rope being referred to.</div><div><strong>Seil</strong> This is a neutral noun in German meaning "rope". It is the thing being described in the sentence and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Seil" to the predicate "am längsten".</div><div><strong>am längsten</strong> This phrase is the superlative form of "lang" (long) in German and translates to "the longest". "Am" is a contraction of "an dem", and in this case, it acts as a part of a superlative structure, which indicates that the rope is longer than all the others in the comparison.</div>','<h2>Dieses Gefühl ist am besten!</h2><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this". It is neuter nominative singular, agreeing in gender and case with the noun it refers to.</div><div><strong>Gefühl</strong> This is a neuter noun in German, meaning "feeling" or "emotion". In this sentence, it is the subject.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It acts as a linking verb connecting the subject to its complement.</div><div><strong>am besten</strong> This is a superlative expression in German. Literally translated as "at the best", it is equivalent to "the best" in English. It’s an adjective phrase describing the noun "Gefühl".</div>','<h2>Ich mag dieses Foto von dir.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like". It expresses a liking or preference towards something.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the accusative case in German, equivalent to "this" in English. It refers to an object close to the speaker, both in terms of distance or relation.</div><div><strong>Foto</strong> This is a neutral noun in the accusative case, which translates to "photo" in English. It is the direct object of the sentence, representing the thing that the speaker likes.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition that can mean "from", "of", or "by" in English. In this sentence, it introduces the object of a possessive, indicating who the photo belongs to or who is pictured in the photo.</div><div><strong>dir</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in the dative case in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It represents to whom the photo belongs or who is depicted in the photo.</div>','<h2>Dieses Restaurant ist Ihres.</h2><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun for "this" in the nominative neuter singular form. It is used here to point to a specific thing (the restaurant) that is close by or currently being discussed.</div><div><strong>Restaurant</strong> This is a German noun for "restaurant", taken directly from the French. It’s in the nominative case because it’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which is "to be" in English. It’s linking the subject of the sentence (das Restaurant) to the possessive pronoun (Ihres).</div><div><strong>Ihres</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the genitive case. It denotes ownership and is related to the informal second-person plural "Ihr", but with a genitive "s" to indicate that the restaurant belongs to the person being spoken to. The capital "I" suggests that it is formal address (Sie-form), implying a singular or plural "you" in English.</div>','<h2>Du singst dieses Lied sehr gut.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence, referring to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>singst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "singen", which means "to sing". In this sentence, it describes the action the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, in its neutral form to agree with the neutral noun "Lied". It translates to "this" in English and is being used to specify the object in question.</div><div><strong>Lied</strong> This is a German noun meaning "song". It is neutral in gender and is the direct object of the verb "singst" in this sentence.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "very". It is used here to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>gut.</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "good". It describes the manner in which the subject sings the song.</div>','<h2>Du wirst dieses Auto reparieren.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English when used in an informal context. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wirst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "werden", which is used to form the future tense in German. It indicates that the action will take place in the future.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in its neutral form in German. It refers to a specific, mentioned thing and is equivalent to "this" in English. It agrees in gender (neuter), number (singular), and case (nominative or accusative) with the noun it is describing or replacing, in this case, "Auto" (car).</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a neuter noun in German that means "car". It’s the direct object of the sentence and is in the accusative case due to the action being performed on it.</div><div><strong>reparieren</strong> This is a verb in the infinitive form meaning "to repair". In this sentence structure, it’s used in combination with the auxiliary verb "werden" to form the future tense, indicating that the subject "you" will perform the action of repairing the car at some point in the future.</div>','<h2>Dieses Auto ist nur ein Modell.</h2><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is the neuter demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this" or "that". It is used here to point to a specific object, in this case, the car.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is the German word for "car" or "automobile". It’s a neuter noun and the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It links the subject "Auto" with the predicate "nur ein Modell".</div><div><strong>nur</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "only" or "just". It’s used to limit or specify the extent of the statement.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the indefinite article in German in the nominative neuter form, meaning "a" or "an" in English. It precedes the noun "Modell" here.</div><div><strong>Modell</strong> This is a German noun meaning "model" or "replica". In this sentence, it refers to a small-scale representation or imitation of the car.</div>','<h2>Ich habe dieses lila Hemd gewählt.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It’s used here to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this" in English. It refers to a near object or matter, agreeing with the noun in gender, number, and case (neuter singular accusative here).</div><div><strong>lila</strong> This is an adjective meaning "purple" in English. In German, adjectives can appear before the noun and they take an ending based on the gender, case, and definiteness of the noun they modify. In this case, "lila" does not change because it is a color adjective that does not usually take an ending.</div><div><strong>Hemd</strong> This is a neuter noun meaning "shirt" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence and it’s in the accusative case due to the action directly affecting it.</div><div><strong>gewählt</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "wählen", which means "to choose" in English. When combined with the auxiliary verb "habe", it forms the present perfect tense, indicating a completed action in the past.</div>','<h2>Dieses Geschenk ist für meinen Sohn.</h2><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is a neuter demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "this" in English. It indicates a specific object close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Geschenk</strong> This is a neuter noun in German, which means "gift" or "present" in English.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the predicate of the sentence.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a preposition in German meaning "for" in English. It indicates the person or object that is the recipient of the action or benefit.</div><div><strong>meinen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular form of the possessive pronoun "mein", which means "my" in English. It denotes possession and agrees in case, gender, and number with the noun it modifies.</div><div><strong>Sohn</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "son" in English.</div>','<h2>Diese Kamera ist ihre.</h2><div><strong>Diese</strong> This German word is a demonstrative adjective meaning "this" in English. It is used in the nominative case and indicates that a specific camera is being discussed.</div><div><strong>Kamera</strong> This is a German noun meaning "camera" in English. It is a feminine noun in the nominative case and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject of the sentence (the camera) to the possessive adjective (ihre).</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is the feminine nominative case or plural form of the possessive pronoun "ihr" in German, which means "her" or "their" in English. It indicates possession, showing that the camera belongs to a female person or to a group of people who have been previously mentioned. The context of the conversation would make it clear whether "ihre" means "her" or "their".</div>','<h2>Diese Information ist für dich.</h2><div><strong>Diese</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun in the feminine nominative singular or neuter nominative and accusative singular, equivalent to "this" in English. It is used to refer to a specific piece of information.</div><div><strong>Information</strong> This is a feminine noun in German, equivalent to "information" in English. In this sentence, it’s the subject on which the sentence is focused.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "for" in English. It indicates the beneficiary or recipient of the information.</div><div><strong>dich</strong> This is the second-person singular accusative pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used here to indicate that the information is intended for the person being spoken to.</div>','<h2>Ja. Ich verstehe diese Frage nicht.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It can be used to affirm a statement or respond affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>verstehe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "verstehen", which means "to understand". It describes the action of understanding something, performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is the German demonstrative adjective meaning "this" in English. It refers to a specific thing or matter that is close to the speaker, in this case, the "Frage" (question).</div><div><strong>Frage</strong> This is the German noun for "question". It’s the direct object of the verb "verstehe", indicating what is not understood by the subject.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb that means "not". It negates the verb, stating that the subject does not understand something.</div>','<h2>Wir haben diese teure Lampe gekauft.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "we". It is the subject of the sentence and denotes the people performing the action of the verb.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the auxiliary verb in German used to form the perfect tense, which translates to "have" in English. It is used in combination with a past participle to indicate a completed action.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this" or "these" in English. It is used to indicate a specific object that is close to the speaker, both in a physical sense and in the context of the conversation. Its gender and number agree with the noun it is referencing, which is feminine singular in this case (Lampe).</div><div><strong>teure</strong> This is the German adjective for "expensive". It describes the noun that follows and agrees with it in terms of gender, case, and number. Here, it is in the nominative case, feminine singular to modify "Lampe".</div><div><strong>Lampe</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in German that means "lamp". It is the direct object of the sentence and is the thing being bought.</div><div><strong>gekauft</strong> This is the past participle of "kaufen", which means "to buy" in German. Combined with the auxiliary verb "haben", it places the action of buying in the past, indicating that the purchase has already been completed.</div>','<h2>Ja, ich werde dich diese Woche anrufen.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It acknowledges or affirms a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which means "to become". In this sentence, it’s used to form the future tense, indicating an action that will happen.</div><div><strong>dich</strong> This is the second-person singular accusative pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence, receiving the action of the call.</div><div><strong>diese Woche</strong> This is a temporal phrase meaning "this week". It indicates when the action of calling will take place.</div><div><strong>anrufen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the separable verb "anrufen" meaning "to call". Combined with the auxiliary verb "werde", it forms the future tense, indicating a planned action.</div>','<h2>Diese Suppe ist besser als die letzte.</h2><div><strong>Diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "this" in English, indicating a closer object, often used here to refer to "this soup".</div><div><strong>Suppe</strong> This is the German noun for "soup" used here in the nominative case as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state or condition of the subject.</div><div><strong>besser</strong> This is the comparative form of the adjective "gut", which means "good" in English. "Besser" stands for "better", comparing two items or states.</div><div><strong>als</strong> This is a conjunction used in German to compare two items or states, equivalent to "than" in English.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the definite article in German for feminine or plural nouns in the nominative case, equivalent to "the" in English. Here it is used before the noun "letzte".</div><div><strong>letzte</strong> This is the superlative form of the adjective "letzt", which means "last" in English. In combination with the definite article "die", it refers to the previous soup mentioned or implied in the conversation.</div>','<h2>Sie haben diese Geschichte zigmal gelesen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "they" in the nominative case, used as the subject of the sentence. It can also mean "you" in the formal singular or plural.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used as an auxiliary verb in constructing the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the accusative case, meaning "this" or "these" in English. It is used to indicate a specific story that is close to the speaker, in terms of distance or time.</div><div><strong>Geschichte</strong> This is a German noun meaning "story" or "history". It’s in the accusative case, making it the direct object of the sentence. Note that nouns are always capitalized in German.</div><div><strong>zigmal</strong> This is an adverb meaning "many times" or "dozens of times". It’s used to express that an action occurred repeatedly.</div><div><strong>gelesen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "lesen", which means "to read". Used with the auxiliary verb "haben", it forms the present perfect tense, indicating a completed action.</div>','<h2>Sie ist nicht an diese Art Hitze gewöhnt.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German third-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "she" or "it" in English, depending on context. In this sentence, it’s the subject and refers to a feminine entity or a formal "you".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It connects the subject to the state of being accustomed or not to something.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not", used to negate a statement.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a German preposition that can mean "on", "at", or "to" depending on the context. In this sentence, it is part of the verbal phrase "gewöhnt sein an" which means "to be accustomed to".</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German meaning "this" or "these". It refers to a specific type or kind of something, agreeing with the noun in gender, number, and case.</div><div><strong>Art</strong> This is a feminine noun in German meaning "type" or "kind". It is used here to classify the kind of heat.</div><div><strong>Hitze</strong> This is a feminine noun in German, meaning "heat". Combined with "diese Art", it refers to a specific type of heat.</div><div><strong>gewöhnt</strong> This is the past participle of "gewöhnen", which means "to get used to" or "to accustom". In combination with "ist", it forms the present perfect tense, indicating a current state (being used to something).</div>','<h2>Okay. Ist nicht wichtig, ich mag diese Farbe.</h2><div><strong>Okay</strong> This is a German word adopted from English and is often used to acknowledge or accept something. It signals agreement or confirmation.</div><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. In this case, it represents the verb "is" as part of the sentence "is not important".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb meaning "not". It negates a statement or parts of a sentence.</div><div><strong>wichtig</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "important". In the sentence, it is negated by "nicht" to convey that something is not important.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the second clause in the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" in English. It indicates a preference or liking for something.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German meaning "this" or "these" when referring to a plural noun or "this" when referring to a feminine or neuter singular noun. It points to a specific object or objects, which is "color" in this case.</div><div><strong>Farbe</strong> This is a German noun meaning "color". It is the direct object in the sentence, and the thing that the speaker likes.</div>','<h2>Wir haben diese Wohnung für ein Jahr gemietet.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used here to form the perfect tense, indicating a completed action.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, which means "this" or "these". It is used here in the accusative case and agrees with the noun "Wohnung" in number and gender (feminine, singular).</div><div><strong>Wohnung</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in German, meaning "apartment" or "flat". It is the direct object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "for", among other definitions. It is used here to indicate the duration of time.</div><div><strong>ein Jahr</strong> This phrase means "one year" in German. It consists of the indefinite article "ein" and the noun "Jahr" and indicates the time period for which the apartment was rented.</div><div><strong>gemietet</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "mieten", which means "to rent". In combination with "haben", it completes the perfect tense of the sentence, indicating that the action of renting has taken place.</div>','<h2>Die Kinder werden sich an diese Reise erinnern.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the German definite article for plural nouns in the nominative case. It translates to "the" in English. It’s used here to refer to a specific group of children.</div><div><strong>Kinder</strong> This is the plural form of the German word "Kind", which means "child". In this sentence, it’s the noun and the subject, referring to the children who will remember the trip.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is the future tense auxiliary verb in German, which corresponds to the English verb "will". It indicates that the action will take place in the future.</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is the reflexive pronoun that corresponds to "themselves" in English. In this sentence, it’s used to indicate that the action of remembering is being done by the subject (the children) to themselves.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a German preposition that is part of the verb phrase "sich erinnern an", which means "to remember". It requires the accusative case when it’s used to express a fixed point in time or space.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the accusative case and plural form. It translates to "this" in English, referring to a specific trip that is understood from the context.</div><div><strong>Reise</strong> This is the German noun for "trip" or "journey", which is the object of the sentence. Here it is in the accusative case because it’s the thing the children will remember.</div><div><strong>erinnern</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "sich erinnern", which means "to remember". In this sentence, it’s used together with the reflexive pronoun "sich" and the auxiliary verb "werden" to form the future tense.</div>','<h2>Diese Äpfel sind unsere.</h2><div><strong>Diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, functioning like "these" in English. It indicates that the following noun "Äpfel" is near in space or time to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Äpfel</strong> This word is the plural form of "Apfel", which means "apple" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Äpfel" with the predicative "unsere".</div><div><strong>unsere</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "our" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the speakers. It is the plural form to agree with "Äpfel".</div>','<h2>Diese Spielsachen sind ihre.</h2><div><strong>Diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German meaning "these". It indicates that the following noun is close to the speaker, both in distance or in terms of emotional connection.</div><div><strong>Spielsachen</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Spielzeug", which means "toys". "Spielsachen" is used to refer to multiple toys or playthings.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It serves as the linking verb in this sentence, connecting the subject to the possessive pronoun.</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German meaning "hers". It indicates that the toys belong to a female person who has already been mentioned or is known from context. The ending "e" indicates that the pronoun corresponds to the plural noun "Spielsachen". If the noun were masculine or neuter and singular, it would be "ihr" without the "e" at the end.</div>','<h2>Sind diese Kleider Ihre?</h2><div><strong>Sind</strong> This is the plural form of the German verb "sein", which means "to be". It is used here to form a question.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is the demonstrative pronoun "these" in English, used to refer to multiple items close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Kleider</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Kleid", meaning "dresses" in English. It refers to more than one piece of clothing.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "yours" in English. In this sentence, it is capitalized because it is the formal form of address in German, referring to either a singular or plural audience. "Ihre" matches the gender and number (feminine plural in this case) of the noun it describes, "Kleider".</div>','<h2>Sind alle diese Schuhe deine?</h2><div><strong>Sind</strong> This is the plural form of the German verb "sein", which means "to be". It is used here for the third-person plural or the formal "you" and is the main verb in the question, here meaning "are".</div><div><strong>alle</strong> This is a German word meaning "all" or "every". It refers to the totality of the items being discussed—in this case, "shoes".</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German meaning "these". It is used to specify which shoes are being talked about, implying they are near the speaker.</div><div><strong>Schuhe</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Schuh", which means "shoe". It is the subject of the sentence being referred to by the pronouns "alle" and "diese".</div><div><strong>deine?</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "dein" in its accusative plural form, which means "your". The possessive pronoun agrees in number and case with "Schuhe". The question mark at the end indicates that this is a question directed at the person being addressed, asking whether the shoes belong to them.</div>','<h2>Alle diese Lutscher sind seine.</h2><div><strong>Alle</strong> This is the German word for "all/every". It indicates that the statement applies to the entirety of the items or people in question.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun for "these". It specifies which items are being talked about and is used to point out the objects that are close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Lutscher</strong> This is a German noun meaning "lollipops". It is in the plural form here, referring to more than one lollipop. In the sentence, "Lutscher" is the object being referred to.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or relationship between the subject and objects in the sentence.</div><div><strong>seine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "his" in English. It denotes ownership, indicating that the lollipops belong to the person being referred to by this pronoun.</div>','<h2>All diese Geschenke sind für dich.</h2><div><strong>All</strong> This is the German word for "all" or "every". It is used here to indicate the totality of the objects being referred to, which is "these gifts" in this context.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is the German demonstrative adjective for "these". It’s used to specify which gifts are being talked about, indicating that they are close to the speaker, either physically or metaphorically.</div><div><strong>Geschenke</strong> This is the plural of the German noun "Geschenk", which means "gift". Here, it is the subject of the sentence, referring to the items being given.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It’s used here to connect the subject "Geschenke" to the phrase indicating for whom the gifts are intended.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This German preposition means "for". It’s used to indicate the beneficiary or recipient of the gifts.</div><div><strong>dich</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in the accusative case in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It identifies the person who is the intended recipient of the gifts.</div>','<h2>Wir möchten diese Äpfel verkaufen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchten</strong> This is the first-person plural conjugation of the modal verb "möchten", indicating a polite form of "want". It expresses a desire or a preference.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in its plural accusative form, which means "these" in English. It is used to specify the apples being referred to.</div><div><strong>Äpfel</strong> This is the plural of the noun "Apfel", which means "apples" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence, being what the subject would like to sell.</div><div><strong>verkaufen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "verkaufen", which means "to sell" in English. Here, it denotes the action that the subject wishes to perform with the apples.</div>','<h2>All diese Äpfel sind sehr ähnlich.</h2><div><strong>All</strong> This is the German word for "all". It is used here to refer collectively to a group of items, in this case, apples.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun in the plural form, meaning "these". It points out specific items that are close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Äpfel</strong> This is the German word for "apples". It is the plural form of "Apfel" and is the subject of this sentence.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the predicate adjective.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It is used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>ähnlich</strong> This is the German adjective meaning "similar". In this sentence, it describes the apples, suggesting that they have alike characteristics or appearances.</div>','<h2>Wir durften diese Bücher ausleihen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "we". It’s the subject of the sentence and denotes the plural form of the first person.</div><div><strong>durften</strong> This is the past tense conjugation of the modal verb "dürfen", which means "to be allowed to" or "may". It expresses permission or possibility in the past tense.</div><div><strong>diese</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, which means "these". It’s used to specify the particular books being talked about.</div><div><strong>Bücher</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Buch", which means "book". In this sentence, it is the direct object, indicating what was allowed to be borrowed.</div><div><strong>ausleihen</strong> This is the German verb meaning "to borrow" or "to lend". It is in the infinitive form because modal verbs like "durften" are usually followed by another verb in the infinitive.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);